a. Using tar, create a tar.gz file of the folder dir1 with the name mydir.tar.gz:

bash

tar -czvf mydir.tar.gz dir1

b. Extract the contents of mydir.tar.gz to dir6:

bash

tar -xzvf mydir.tar.gz -C dir1/dir6

c. Use top to display processes sorted on:
i. ProcessId:

bash

top -o PID

ii. CPU%:

bash

top -o %CPU

d. Use ps to display:
i. Processes associated with the current terminal:

bash

ps T

ii. All processes in the system:

bash

ps aux

e. Use df to display the storage available in each partition in human-readable form:

bash

df -h
